INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a1b13808-c270-45bd-ae19-8b84a0ba0bb2',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Astro Server Actions — Treating the Server Boundary as a Security Boundary$escape$,
  $escape$Astro Server Actions (`src/actions/index.ts`) form a hard trust boundary — they execute exclusively on the server but are invocable from any `.astro` component or client island via `actions` from `astro:actions`. That boundary is only as strong as your validation.

Every action accepting client input must declare an `input` Zod schema. Astro validates against it automatically and surfaces a typed `ActionInputError` on failure — skip it and you're trusting raw POST bodies. The `handler` only receives parsed, safe input after the schema passes.

Env var separation is equally critical. Astro exposes `import.meta.env` to both client and server contexts. Any variable without the `PUBLIC_` prefix is stripped from client bundles at build time — but a typo (`PUBLISHABLE_KEY` instead of `PUBLIC_PUBLISHABLE_KEY`) silently ships secrets. Use Astro 5's `astro:env` module with `envField.string({ context: "server", access: "secret" })` to turn accidental client exposure into a build-time error, not a runtime leak.

Within `handler`, authenticate via `ctx.locals` (populated by your middleware) — never derive auth state from user-controlled request headers.$escape$,
  $escape$// src/actions/index.ts
import { defineAction, ActionError } from "astro:actions";
import { z } from "astro:schema";

export const server = {
  submitPost: defineAction({
    input: z.object({
      title: z.string().min(1).max(120),
      url: z.string().url(),
    }),
    handler: async (input, ctx) => {
      if (!ctx.locals.auth().userId)
        throw new ActionError({ code: "UNAUTHORIZED" });
      const apiKey = import.meta.env.INTERNAL_API_KEY; // server-only, no PUBLIC_ prefix
    },
  }),
};$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
