INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'b679f277-1ce8-45f9-aa9a-2a0fa4f10bf0',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Astro Web Vitals — Image Optimization, Font Loading, and LCP with astro:assets$escape$,
  $escape$Astro's `<Image />` component from `astro:assets` automatically converts images to WebP/AVIF, injects explicit `width`/`height` attributes to eliminate layout shift (CLS), and generates optimized srcsets — zero config. For LCP, the critical flag is `loading="eager"` combined with `fetchpriority="high"` on your above-the-fold hero image. Without this, browsers deprioritize the image during speculative parsing, killing your LCP score.

For fonts, skip Google Fonts CDN entirely. Host font files locally under `public/fonts/`, then `<link rel="preload">` them in your layout's `<head>`. Pair this with `font-display: swap` in CSS. Astro layouts give you direct `<head>` control — no framework abstraction in the way.

Use `<Picture />` when you need art direction or want to ship AVIF with a WebP fallback. The `formats` prop controls output types, and `widths` + `sizes` drives responsive behavior. Avoid raw `<img>` tags for any content images — you lose the sharp image service pipeline entirely, including the build-time dimension inference that prevents CLS.$escape$,
  $escape$---
import { Image, Picture } from 'astro:assets';
import heroImg from '../assets/hero.jpg';
---

<!-- LCP hero: eager load + high fetch priority -->
<Image
  src={heroImg}
  alt="Hero"
  loading="eager"
  fetchpriority="high"
  widths={[640, 1280, 1920]}
  sizes="100vw"
/>

<!-- Art-directed responsive image -->
<Picture
  src={heroImg}
  formats={['avif', 'webp']}
  widths={[400, 800]}
  sizes="(max-width: 640px) 400px, 800px"
  alt="Feature"
/>$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
