INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'eea9f651-c0ef-4478-9031-f4d2ccc4366e',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Astro Memory Leaks — Abort Signals in SSR Streaming and View Transitions Cleanup$escape$,
  $escape$Astro's SSR streaming sends HTML incrementally as async components resolve. If the client disconnects mid-stream, `Astro.request.signal` fires — but downstream `fetch()` calls inside `.astro` files or API routes won't cancel unless you explicitly forward that signal. In any SSR page, destructure and thread it through every fetch. In API routes, pull it from `APIContext`. If your endpoint spawns its own `AbortController`, chain it: listen for `Astro.request.signal` abort and call `controller.abort()` in that handler.

View Transitions introduces a second leak vector. With `<ViewTransitions />` active, client scripts from the outgoing page survive until the swap phase completes. Any `setInterval`, `EventSource`, or streaming fetch initialized in a `<script>` block keeps running on the next route. Cancel them in `astro:before-preparation`, which fires before Astro fetches the next page's HTML — earlier than `astro:before-swap`, giving pending requests time to terminate cleanly. Always pass `{ once: true }` to the listener; without it, the handler itself accumulates across navigations and fires multiple times per transition.$escape$,
  $escape$---
// src/pages/feed.astro — SSR mode
const { signal } = Astro.request;
const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/feed', { signal });
const items = await res.json();
---

<script>
  let controller = new AbortController();

  const stream = () => {
    controller = new AbortController();
    fetch('/api/live', { signal: controller.signal }).catch(() => {});
  };

  document.addEventListener('astro:before-preparation', () => {
    controller.abort();
  }, { once: true });

  stream();
</script>$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
